               <scopecontent id="aspace_76f55a69c4c46b7aa7aae0bb65f3cd18">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>After losing his seat in the Lords in 1734, Stair retired to Scotland and devoted himself to organizing the opposition to Walpole there. These letters were written to inform Stair of developments in London. They contain gossip about Walpole, George II (his quarrels with the prince of Wales and the death and funeral of Queen Caroline), the Duke of Argyle, and other members of the opposition. The Duchess also writes at length about parliamentary and foreign affairs in a more general way and discusses difficulties with her own family. One letter contains an interesting passage on Jonathan Swift.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
